[1]
Date: Fri, 04 Apr 1997 16:14:12 -0400 (EDT)
From: David O. Matson <matson@picard.evms.edu>
I hate to sound picky here, but do the persons who could know have absolute
confirmation that the syndrome in the pigs in Taiwan IS the foot-and-mouth
syndrome caused by foot-and-mouth disease virus?
For 30+ years we attempted to eradicate "foot-and-mouth" syndrome among pigs
in the U.S., only to realize that the syndrome did not affect cows on the
same farms as the affected pigs and that the causative agent was vesicular
exanthema of swine virus, a calicivirus. Genetic and epidemiologic studies
have established a link between the pig isolates of those outbreaks and
isolates from marine sources are related (see for example J Zoo Wildl Med
1990;21:3 and Arch Virol 1996;141:2443).
I'd hate for all this effort and concern with the Taiwan pork to be
attributed to the wrong virus, with different epidemiologic implications.
---
David O. Matson, M.D., Ph.D.
Center for Pediatric Research
Norfolk, Virginia
matson@picard.evms.edu
[For those who don't know, the standard response of all countries is to
refer their isolates of "FMDV" to the relevant FAO FMD reference laboratory.
The FAO regional laboratory is in Bangkok, Thailand, and the world reference
laboratory is in Pirbright, UK. Through contacts I will check. I would be
surprised if the UK Government would supply FMD vaccine to Taiwan without
confirmation.
However, though I am sure that if I am wrong I will be rapidly corrected, I
belive that vesicular exanthema has not been seen in North American
livestock in many decades; the feeding of dead sea lions to pigs was
stopped, I think, in the early 1950s and with that outbreaks of VE in pigs.
But another disease - swine vesicular disease - can be confused clinically
with FMD and SVD originated in China. As with VE, SVD does not affect
cattle. And it is notable that in the press reports there have been no
accounts of cases in Taiwanese dairy farms and in sheep & goats. Information
is being sought from OIE. MHJ]
