[3]
Date: Sat, 5 Apr 1997 11:13:45 +0800
From: bunny <rabbit@wantree.com.au>
culled from The Straits Times, APR 1 1997
Taiwan meat packers and officials held widely publicised festive pork
"eat-ins" yesterday in an islandwide campaign to ease public fears over an
epidemic, handing out free steaks, sweet-and-sour pork and a Chinese
favourite -- stewed pig trotters. The trotters were crucial after days of
graphic television news coverage of the mass slaughter of thousands of swine
with the tell-tale symptoms of foot-and-mouth disease -- infected hooves.
"Tasty, juicy, you really want to take a bite!" said the slogan under a
colour picture of a steaming trotter splashed across top newspapers' front
pages in advertisements bought by hard-hit meat packers and feed firms.
"When was the last time you savoured a delectable pork trotter?" said
another. Many Taiwan consumers have not touched pork since March 20, when
the Cabinet's Council of Agriculture confirmed that it had found FMD,
ordered a ban on exports, and initiated a massive slaughter and vaccination
programme. Much rides on the success of the massive trotter promotion, as
pork prices are 60 per cent or more below their pre-epidemic levels. Pork
trading resumed on Saturday at the island's major hog wholesale centres,
most of which suspended operations last Monday in a failed bid to bolster
prices. The shutdown gave meat packers time to launch the drive to restore
confidence.
As of late Friday [4th April], FMD had been detected on 1,008 of the
island's 25,000 farms, with officials projecting that 886,000 pigs would
have to be destroyed, although only 160,315 had been slaughtered to date.
The Consumers' Foundation said people should ask pork sellers for
certificates proving their meats were safe and should not fear eating
certified pork. Such certificates have been appearing in restaurant windows
and grocery meat departments across Taiwan.
